nodes.title: Step 3 - Depth Maps
widgets_values:
First thing I do with most videos is grab a depth map.

There are a few choices here for preprocessing, Depth anything is best all around for most videos, but it's not always the best for every video.  

Connect the preprocessor you wish to use to the depth node. Default is depth anything

Preview/Save depth is to preview the depth map and to save when ready.  The save output option will save a Mp4 video file of the depth map.  

Default directory is inside your projects / video name folder

nodes.title: Remove BG for controls
widgets_values:
Removeing the background for controls.

If you have a decent mask generated you can load it in here to remove the background of the video before you process the openpose, lineart or any others. 

This can remove background people from the video control files as long as your masks removed them.

This works for lineart, openpose, and extras.

nodes.title: Simple Masking
widgets_values:
V5
Removed A LOT of un needed things.
SAM masking separate flow, better masking solution when it works

7 steps - 
frames save (image or video) - audio save
depth save (image or video)
Masking save (video) Sam 1 segs or remove background options

The following can use a mask to remove the backgound before processing
linearts save (video)
pose save (video) person or animal

All files are saved to the projects folder in the video name folder you choose.

Optional
Pose face mask save
Face mesh and Extra controls save

removed
anime masking
threshold masking
combine depth segs
remove watermarks (moved to videos workflow)


Update 4.1
- added Depth Anything v2
- added dense pose saving for testing
- added proper saving locations, now all control net files are saved to the projects folder inside the chosen video folder for easier sorting
note - all files still need to be renamed to remove the 00001 extensions.
- added proper switch to change the save directory name


This has been reworked to remove all unneeded things, to make black and white masks only for a fast and easy to use masking solution.  An advanced workflow will come with many of the options removed from this, but for 90% of people this should do what you are looking for in a clear manner.

*********** Warning *********** 

This workflow has been tested to process up to 800 frames in a batch however this is VERY VERY SYSTEM MEMORY INTENSIVE!
Processing 800 frames quickly fills my 32gb of system memory many times over.  Having a LARGE system page file WILL help.

Features
Video saving with sound
Depth Saving
Open Pose / Animal Pose Saving
Segmentation/SAM masking, depth masking, mix masking edited masking, watermark mask removal
Media pipe face mesh saving
Face masking saving options

This workflow requires SYSTEM MEMORY for large videos.  Vram is less important.  

First, I want to be clear, you don't need masks to copy a video.  You can choose to just save a clip and the depth map/open pose files. 

The reasons I use masks, is for one of 2 reasons. 
- I want to replace the background with something else entirely.  (inpaint or control net)
- I want to ensure a stable background copy while still allowing me to change the subject by large amounts. (inpaint or control net)

Without a mask, you rely on lower weighted depth/stabilizer controls to hold the background stable.  It can work, but using a mask allows you to use full strength control nets on the background while using weaker ones on the subject to hold and not allow the AI to start to wander too far in background generation while allowing it more room to change the subject.

nodes.title: START Step 1
widgets_values:
Start here
This area loads the video and sets the default directory for the project

The default Projects folder is what this entire flow set is based on.  
Inside comfy ui you have a output directory.  Inside here we will place a Projects folder to store ALL videos, controls, masks, and all else related to each video
All of this is done automaticly if you run this flow for your desired video.

The default video import directory is confyui\input\   You can change this to where you store your videos if you wish.

Loading options

- Video file name is the file name of the video you are loading, 
This is both used for loading the video and for saving the files in the projects folder.  A folder will be created in output/Projects/ "this name" / to save all controlnets
- video type is the extension of the video.

This sets the folder name that is created inside the projects folder mentioned above.  By default this is named to the same as the video you are loading.  You can change the folder name by using the switch and text box in red below the video file name.  This is usefull when pulling multiple clips from the same video to seperate them into different folders.


-Frame Load cap limits the number of frames letting you set the number of frames to process at a time.  You can set any number you want that you can process at a time with your specs. (you can use the frame number viewer to the left to see where frame cuts are to process each scene seperately)
-Skip every lets you skip frames, lowering the FPS and the number of images you need to process.  I recommend doing full frames at 1 then limiting it in the video creation step.  But you do you and limit it how you wish (the fps of the loaded frames is shown to show you what the output video will be)
-Skipping first - This shows you how many frames the current batch is skipping


Below this loader is the on, off options for all groups.  You can enable everything there.  The arrows in the switches will take you to the groups to do the settings.


My biggest tips,
save everything, then use what works in the video flow, I will end with 4-5 mask sets, 2 depth, and a few open poses.. Just because I don't want to come back here to redo something.
Get this right and the video flow is MUCH easier because when something does not work well, you have other options without reloading this flow.

nodes.title: Cropping and Sizing
widgets_values:
Cropping and rescaling

I dont recomened rescaling the video too small.  I usually run the full video for best results, however anything above 1080p can be hard to process expecially for large frame sets

Cropping can be done before any processing is done.  This can allow you to cut out areas you dont want or put it in a new perspective.

nodes.title: Step 4 - Segmentation SAM
widgets_values:
I highly recommend using SAM 2 masking in a seperate flow.  When it works, it does a better job and allows separation of subjects and objects.

This can save any mask, not just subject, faces, hands, etc can be masked and saved here to be loaded into the video flow

This area uses Segmentation or SAM to mask your subject.  Segmentation is very fast and can be good enough for most uses.  Sam is slow but more accurate.  Sam takes more tinkering to get the settings correct for each video

Seg Model choices are what works best for you.
SAM works well, it's close to depth for accuracy, but can miss.  Its slow and takes more tinkering with the settings to get what you want and can sometimes just fail on some videos.  Segs is usually accurate enough.

Bbox threshold determines what is detected as a person.  Lower this, someone is not detected or missing in a frame.  

Drop size will remove white areas smaller than it.

Sub Threshold determines how accurate it needs to be to mask something.  
-Lowering this expands the mask, as it does not need to be as sure that it identified part of a person. 
-Raising this shrinks the mask as it needs a higher accuracy in determining what is a person.

Saving

Default directory is inside your projects / video name folder

nodes.title: Step 4 - Remove Background
widgets_values:
Remove background masking option

Fast and simple, but works decent for simple videos

Choose the model to use, human seg and general purpose do well in simple situations, and anime illustrations does well for cartoon/anime videos.

Saving

Default directory is inside your projects / video name folder

nodes.title: Step 4 - Depth Masking
widgets_values:
With a depth map, we can attempt to make a mask from it.

Once enabled this will take in your depth map and with a threshold convert that to a mask.  You will need to play with the threshold for each video.  

Up brings in less.
Down brings in more.

Try to get the subject/s upper body and as close as you can to the feet in the mask.  Whatever they are standing on (ground, floor etc) will be there most likely.  Keep raising the threshold until you start to lose the subjects in the mask, then back off again. some can be 20 some can be 210.  You need to experiment with each video.  Be careful checking as small areas like feet, arms, hair need to be checked each change. 

This is a fast process once depth is created, so should not take long to find your best number.

Default directory is inside your projects / video name folder

Depth notes

If depth anything gives you a bad depth map with little contrast.  Try Zoe depth anything indoor or outdoor.  It's slower but offers higher contrast for further off subjects.

Depth anything V2 added, have not tested it much but it seems to hold much more detail in the output

Midas tends to make good masks because it can separate the floors better and does decent for contrast.

You can limit the frames to a few to test each one, but you should know the distance from camera changes contrast for each.
